TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of Americanization on the Earnings of Foreign-born Men
AU  - Chiswick, Barry R.
Y1  - 1978/10/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260717
DO  - 10.1086/260717
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 897
EP  - 921
VL  - 86
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The earnings of foreign-born adult white men, as reported in the 1970 Census of Population, are analyzed through comparisons with the native born and among the foreign born by country of origin, years in the United States, and citizenship. Differences in the effects of schooling and postschool training are explored. Although immigrants initially earn less than the native born, their earnings rise more rapidly with U.S. labor market experience, and after 10 to 15 years their earnings equal, and then exceed, that of the native born. Earnings are unrelated to whether the foreign born are U.S. citizens.
AB  - The earnings of foreign-born adult white men, as reported in the 1970 Census of Population, are analyzed through comparisons with the native born and among the foreign born by country of origin, years in the United States, and citizenship. Differences in the effects of schooling and postschool training are explored. Although immigrants initially earn less than the native born, their earnings rise more rapidly with U.S. labor market experience, and after 10 to 15 years their earnings equal, and then exceed, that of the native born. Earnings are unrelated to whether the foreign born are U.S. citizens.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260717
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260717
Y2  - 2024/03/22
