T1  - A Note on Some Evidence on the Easterlin Hypothesis
AU  - Olneck, Michael R.
AU  - Wolfe, Barbara L.
Y1  - 1978/10/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260720
DO  - 10.1086/260720
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 953
EP  - 958
VL  - 86
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - According to the Easterlin hypothesis, the positive relationship between income and fertility is dependent on relative income. The hypothesis presumes that aspirations are significantly determined by family background. If income is high relative to aspirations, individuals will tend to have more children. The definition of variables as sibling differences controls family background and yields a measure of relative income. Analyzing the Kalamazoo Brothers sample in this fashion produces no evidence in support of the hypothesis.
AB  - According to the Easterlin hypothesis, the positive relationship between income and fertility is dependent on relative income. The hypothesis presumes that aspirations are significantly determined by family background. If income is high relative to aspirations, individuals will tend to have more children. The definition of variables as sibling differences controls family background and yields a measure of relative income. Analyzing the Kalamazoo Brothers sample in this fashion produces no evidence in support of the hypothesis.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260720
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260720
Y2  - 2024/03/22
